==Short Description==

Slock.it is a German company having the vision of creating an all-embracing sharing network to rent or share any asset over the Ethereum Blockchain (main chain). Because assets need to have an internet connection in order to be shared over blockchain-based applications, Slock.it also aims to offer solutions in the field of the Internet of Things (IoT). Their main product will be the Universal Sharing Network (USN), a decentralized and open-source infrastructure where assets can be shared for financial gain.<ref name=„website“/><ref name=„usn“/> To connect assets to the Ethereum Blockchain, Slock.it started to develop another product, the so-called IOT Layer. This project aims to offer a comprehensive software framework for the gateway between physical IoT devices and the virtual blockchain so that they can be shared on the blockchain. The IOT Layer offers payment channels (on- and off-chain), hub services, a marketplace for assets and access control to the connected IoT devices. Furthermore, the IOT Layer integrates IoT devices into existing IoT clouds and IoT environments. By empowering machines to send and receive transactions, it also enables Machine to Machine and Machine to Human interactions.<ref name=„iotlayer“>https://iot.slock.it/iotlayer.html, accessed on 02.07.2018.</ref> In addition, the „Incubed“-client will be part of the IOT Layer offering the possibility to connect to multiple chains without storing any parts of the blockchain. The proposed solution works in a trustless environment. For this purpose, devices are connected to various nodes that are incentivized to provide correct information only to requests of the IoT device. These features allow the client to be installed even on small IoT devices.<ref name=„blog1“>https://blog.slock.it/slock-it-iot-layer-f305601df963, accessed on 02.07.2018.</ref> Bringing it all together, the user experience could be as follows: Alice would like to rent a bike using the USN. She opens the Slock.it mobile application and looks for available bicycles close-by. Once she finds a bike, Alice sends a transaction to the access control smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain containing the payment for renting the bike and a collateral. The smart contract controls the bike’s smart lock and is thereby able to unlock it. Subsequently, Alice opens the lock by sending a bluetooth signal to the lock allowing her to use the bike for the specified conditions. As soon as Alice returns the bike, the deposit is released automatically by the smart contract and the remaining Ethers are sent to the owner of the bike.<ref name=„youtube“>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7BKegezSXIU, accessed on 16.07.2018.</ref><ref name=„usn“/>


